minted_nfts.name: Bom Dia #34
minted_nfts.description:
Instructions of use:
1 Use a dispositive equipped with camera
2 Enable Advanced Mode (under the token screen, after application/x-directory)
3 If asked, allow browser to access the camera
4 Click on the image
5 Press '1' in keyboard to download png
6 Share your Bom Dia
7 Some iterations allow the use of two or three faces together.

Bom Dia, or Good Morning, is an interactive application written in JavaScript with the support of p5.js and ml5.js. Activated through facial recognition, the work greets each visitor with a personalized GM, composed of a shifting assemblage of images, typefaces, phrases, and GIF stickers that frame the user’s face. The project examines the everyday circulation of Bom Dia images as part of Brazilian and Latin American digital folklore. Affectionate in tone and deeply entangled with Christian imaginaries, these messages quietly sustain meritocratic narratives and work-ethic ideologies, urging subjects to endure yet another day under capitalism.

Estelle Flores and Érica Storer, 2025. 

Disclaimer: This application uses machine learning to detect your face. Images from your camera are not stored in any way. We do not own any gifs and characters used in the application.

minted_nfts.name: Cortafuegos
minted_nfts.description:
This work was created in the analog glitch workshop led by Rocio mio from Bosque Gracias at bosque gracias residency 2026, just a few days before the fire took the houses and the forest. The running water is a small part of the Epuyén River, which now flows within us too.

"Cortafuegos" is a short loop that seeks to concentrate all the energies of the water and the community.
Bosque Gracias was a refuge for many of us and will continue to be; 
it was a temple that honors nature and will continue to be. 
It was a place to remember the ancient and profound connection between human beings and nature, and it will continue to be. 
It is a place to understand that nothing is lost, and that the future belongs to the human who immeasurably embraces Mother Earth.

There is a poem by the Argentine singer-songwriter José Luis Aguirre that portrays this kind of place very well:

Menos mal que tenemos nuestros lugares de encuentro
Lugares con corazón, lugares tierra, lugares casa
O como bien lo dijo el compadre Orlando el otro día
"De resistencia, de esperanza"
Donde atrincherarnos, abrazarnos, acovacharnos
Lugares y que venga el agua que de acá no nos mueve naides
Rincones, rinconcitos, que reverdecen con cada estío
Desde el crepitante despertar de un vino
Hasta el nuevo cancionero de los asados
A pesar de lo grotesco y el olvido
A pesar de tanto hachazo
Lugares lumbre, con alma
Donde se nos arremolina un caterío de hijos por las patas
Mientras heredan, atestiguan la
Imprescindible continuación de la magia
Y se manchan lindo los compadres
Y se tejen las comadres y se ríen y se gastan
Y anda un pueblo entero empujándose al barro
Como críos recién vividos con la lluvia
Lugares patio, lugares patria
Lejos, lejos de las luces de esos grandes festivales latifundistas
Que pretenden homenajear el fruto del trabajo de un obrero
De un peón que después no puede pagarse la entrada
Ni darse el gusto del locro ritual y las empanadas
Ni entrarle fiero al trago olvidador de las penurias del fiado
No mi amigo, yo digo otros lugares
Más en la intemperie, más en lo espontáneo
Lugares fuego, lugares bombo, río, murga, trasnoche, mesa larga
Y que nos venga el ángel igualador de la chaya
Agigantado con la harina
O en todo caso con el arroz, con los
Porotos, con los fideos, con lo que haiga
Para luego caer a la inquebrantable voluntad de una olla comunitaria
Suerte amigos que están nuestros lugares
Y que estamos armados hasta las muelas
Con canciones y con danzas
Porque tenemos feroces panteras de poesía
Y perros huesudos que muerden el duro costado de la ignorancia
Menos mal que tenemos San Antonio, La Pirincha, Los Poetas
Y allá en la lomita La Juntada
Si así no fuera, qué fácil nos comería la nada
Lugares duende, beso, vizcachera, piedra sagrada
O como bien lo dijo el compadre el otro día

minted_nfts.name: Pneuma
minted_nfts.description:
Pneuma takes its name from the ancient concept of breath as both a physical force and a metaphysical principle. In Greek philosophy, pneuma signifies breath, air, spirit — the invisible substance that animates matter and connects body to world. This work operates within that threshold, where a bodily act becomes a formative event.

The drawing is not constructed through line in the traditional sense, but through exhalation. Ink is displaced by breath, pushed beyond the hand’s direct control. What appears on the surface is the residue of a moment in which intention yields to physiology: lungs, pressure, duration, and exhaustion all participate in shaping the form. The mark is therefore not drawn, but released.

Breath functions here as a mediator between inside and outside. It is an intimate gesture — internal, involuntary, rhythmic — yet it manifests externally, altering matter. In this sense, the work records a transfer: the interior state of the body translated into visible disruption. Ink responds not as a passive medium, but as a substance with its own resistance, viscosity, and memory. The resulting form is neither fully authored nor accidental, but negotiated.

The composition suggests force, rupture, and directional collapse, yet these qualities emerge without violence. They are produced through an act essential to life itself. This tension situates Pneuma between control and vulnerability, asserting breath as both a tool and a limit. The drawing becomes a document of presence — evidence that a body was here, breathing, exerting, and momentarily imprinting itself onto matter.

Ultimately, Pneuma proposes drawing as an event rather than an image. It asks the viewer not to read the work symbolically, but to encounter it as a trace of lived time — a moment when breath, ink, and surface aligned, and form briefly came into being.

minted_nfts.name: Inked
minted_nfts.description:
Inked is an exploration of matter before meaning.
Ink appears here not as a tool of description, but as an event — a substance that records motion, hesitation, pressure, and accident all at once. Each mark exists between intention and surrender, where control is initiated but never completed.

The forms suggest orbits, cells, or voids, yet they resist becoming fixed symbols. Instead, they remain unstable, as if still in the process of forming. Ink spreads, pools, interrupts itself; it remembers gravity and time more than it obeys design. What emerges is a field of traces rather than figures — evidence of contact rather than representation.

In this work, ink functions as both body and memory. It carries the residue of an action that has already passed, asking the viewer not to interpret what is shown, but to witness what has happened.

A quiet, looping meditation on complicity, ambition, and the cost of survival in systems that reward deference.

minted_nfts.description:
The brand is a celebration soaked in the rhythms of salsa and the taste of freedom. It shows two friends in the middle of a carnival night. The abstract shapes of the faces and the vivid contrasts of yellow, red and blue convey the very energy that cannot be described in words — only felt.

The texture of the stamp resembles an old mural on the wall of a colonial building or rough handmade paper. This issue is dedicated to the ability to enjoy the moment. The "Soul of Havana" stamp is used for the most sincere and emotional messages that carry a charge of warmth and joy.
